title: London School of Emerging Technology Announces New Expert-Led Series on Advanced AI Innovations | User | bigspringherald.com
text:
LSET Expert Series on AI-Based Concepts Like SIMA Google DeepMind Expert and Devin AI Featuring Insights from SIMA and Google DeepMind Specialists, the Series Aims to Demystify Latest Developments in AI, Including Devin AI Breakthroughs London, UK - 11th April, 2024 - The London School of Emerging Technology (LSET) proudly announces its latest initiative aimed at revolutionising the educational landscape in the field of artificial intelligence. Presenting the groundbreaking Expert Series , LSET offers an exclusive opportunity to explore two cutting-edge AI technologies - SIMA Google DeepMind Expert and Devin AI, the pioneer in AI software engineering. Admissions for this unparalleled opportunity will close by April 15th.
SIMA: Google's DeepMind Expert
At the vanguard of AI innovation stands SIMA, an exceptional generalist AI Agent poised to transform the field. SIMA transcends conventional limitations, serving as a virtual companion proficient in executing diverse tasks across virtual environments, from embarking on adventures in fantastical realms to crafting intricate digital structures.
SIMA's prowess lies in its ability to comprehend natural language instructions, enabling seamless interaction with users. What distinguishes SIMA is its unique capacity to learn and adapt, continuously evolving its intelligence through user engagement and experiences. Developed through a groundbreaking collaboration between Google and leading game developers, SIMA represents a significant milestone in AI development, bridging the gap between language and tangible actions.
Devin: The World's First AI Software Engineer
Enter Devin AI, a revolutionary advancement in AI systems' understanding and interpretation of human emotions. Leveraging cutting-edge natural language processing (NLP) and machine learning (ML) algorithms, Devin AI discerns subtle nuances in human speech and behavior, accurately identifying emotions ranging from joy to frustration.
What truly sets Devin AI apart is its autonomous operation, capable of overseeing entire software development projects from inception to deployment. This encompasses a spectrum of tasks, including planning, coding, debugging, and execution, showcasing its proficiency in managing complex engineering endeavors independently.
SIMA operates on the principle of understanding human language, facilitating seamless interpretation of commands and execution of tasks across diverse virtual environments. Through continuous interaction and learning, SIMA evolves its intelligence, progressively enhancing its ability to fulfill user requests.
Meanwhile, Devin AI integrates machine learning, deep learning, and natural language processing technologies to automate and elevate software development tasks. With its comprehensive development tools and real-time collaboration capabilities, Devin AI streamlines the software development process, empowering engineers to focus on higher-level skills.
Mr. Mayur Ramgir, Principal Instructor at LSET, emphasised, “Our commitment to educating students on the technology behind SIMA Google's DeepMind Expert and Devin AI underscores LSET's dedication to delivering cutting-edge education in emerging technologies. Such initiatives are poised to reshape the landscape of AI and software development, equipping students with the skills and knowledge needed to thrive in an increasingly digitized world. As AI continues to permeate various sectors, more job opportunities will arise, and the demand for skilled professionals proficient in these technologies is expected to soar.” Registration fee for the Expert Series is £25, and detailed information regarding the series and enrollment procedure is available at Expert Series Website .

author: Judy Sanhz
title: Some older D-Link routers are vulnerable to attack | Digital Trends
text:
Getty Images A few legacy D-Link routers can be vulnerable to Remote Code Execution (RCE) attacks since the company refuses to send any updates to patch them up, claiming they have reached end-of-life, as recently posted on its announcement page .
The vulnerability is a serious issue since it allows hackers to take control from anywhere in the world and use a stack buffer overflow. This attack sends more data than the buffer size can handle, potentially corrupting critical information like the return address. Thus, hackers can take control of your PC. However, the company did not detail how the threat works, possibly not informing the hackers too much about the issue.
Recommended Videos The lack of a fix puts users at risk since they are exposed to malware, data theft, spyware installation, DoS attacks, and more. The routers that are at risk include the following:
DSR-150 DSR-150N DSR-250 DSR-250N DSR-500N DSR-1000N The company’s only solution for those affected is to get a new router, and if that’s what you’re going to do, you may as well buy one of the best routers . Unfortunately, though , four of the listed routers were discontinued this year, which is bad news considering D-Link said, “If a product has reached End of Support (“EOS”) / End of Life (“EOL”), there is normally no further extended support or development for it.”
Related AMD Ryzen 7 5800X3D details leak, and there’s some bad news TP-Link’s new Kasa mesh router doubles as an Alexa smart speaker The 20% discount D-Link offers on new routers is a nice gesture, but the report says many of the listed routers are open to third-party firmware. That’s not a great solution since it voids the warranty.
But let’s face it: when a device becomes obsolete, it makes sense that the company wants to forget about it and concentrate on the new models.

author: EFE
title: Casa Blanca descarta dar indulto a Julian Assange | Radio Fórmula
text: La Casa Blanca afirmó este jueves que no está considerando otorgar un perdón presidencial al f [undador de WikiLeaks, Julian Assange](https://www.radioformula.com.mx/mundo/2024/6/26/assange-ya-esta-en-australia-arriba-al-pais-tras-quedar-en-libertad-por-acuerdo-con-eu-822003.html), como lo han solicitado sus abogados. La portavoz de la Casa Blanca, Karine Jean-Pierre, respondió con un escueto "no" cuando los periodistas a bordo del avión presidencial Air Force One le preguntaron si se estaba considerando esa opción. La pregunta surgió a raíz de las declaraciones de los abogados de Assange y de su esposa, Stella Assange, quienes en las últimas horas anunciaron que pedirán al presidente de Estados Unidos, Joe Biden, un perdón presidencial con el objetivo de limpiar el historial delictivo de Assange. Esta semana, Assange selló con el Departamento de Justicia de EU un acuerdo judicial por el que se declaró culpable de un cargo penal relacionado con la mayor filtración de documentos clasificados de la historia de Estados Unidos, ocurrida en 2010 y que cuestionó el papel de ese país en el mundo al revelar atrocidades en las guerras de Irak y Afganistán. Assange ya es hombre libre A cambio de reconocer su responsabilidad, Assange fue condenado formalmente a 62 meses de cárcel, pero se le dio crédito por el tiempo que ya había cumplido en una prisión de alta seguridad en el Reino Unido. De esta manera, pudo salir en libertad y regresar a su Australia natal. El fundador de WikiLeaks llegó el miércoles a Camberra, Australia en un avión privado después de haber formalizado el pacto para su libertad ante un juez de las Islas Marianas del Norte (EU), tras pasar cinco años recluido en el Reino Unido y otros casi siete refugiado en la embajada de Ecuador en Londres. "Tras casi 14 años de detención arbitraria en Reino Unido, y 5 años en una prisión de máxima seguridad por su trabajo innovador, Julian Assange ha regresado a casa en Australia", apuntó WikiLeaks en su cuenta de X. El australiano fue recibido en la pista de aterrizaje por su esposa, Stella Assange, a quien besó y con quien se fundió en un abrazo, y por su padre, el arquitecto australiano John Shipton.

author: ESPN News Services
title: Heat's Jimmy Butler (calf) to miss fourth consecutive game - ESPN
text: [Miami Heat](/nba/team/_/name/mia/miami-heat) star forward [Jimmy Butler](http://www.espn.com/nba/player/_/id/6430/jimmy-butler) has been ruled out of Thursday's game against the host [Golden State Warriors](/nba/team/_/name/gs/golden-state-warriors) due to a calf injury. This will be Butler's fourth consecutive game sidelined by his injury. The Heat also announced guard [Kyle Lowry](http://www.espn.com/nba/player/_/id/3012/kyle-lowry) (soreness) and forward [Caleb Martin](http://www.espn.com/nba/player/_/id/3138160/caleb-martin) (ankle) will sit out Thursday's game in San Francisco, the first of a five-game road trip. Guard [Josh Richardson](http://www.espn.com/nba/player/_/id/2581190/josh-richardson) (back) remains doubtful for the contest. Butler, 34, averages 21.5 points and 5.2 rebounds to go along with a team-leading 4.6 assists in 23 games (all starts) this season. Lowry, 37, contributes 9.4 points, 4.1 assists and 3.7 rebounds in 28 games (all starts) in 2023-24. Martin, 28, averages 11.0 points, 5.1 rebounds and 2.3 assists in 20 games (10 starts) this season. Field Level Media contributed to this report.
